Ask HN: Layered Design or Flat Design?
text:
I am writing a web app with the intention of evolving the app as and when the requirements evolve.

While writing the code I am faced with the dilemma of whether to just provide mechanisms at the lower level and push the policy handling at the higher levels, or just flatten the design and handle both mechanism and policies at the same level.

There are pros and cons of both approaches.

So how does one overcome this dilemma when dealing with evolving requirements?

Ask HN: Could the Wallaby EV NEV be a reason for Russia to change course?
text:
Hello, as the inventor of the Wallaby EV, a clean-sheet innovation in the US DOT Neighborhood Electric Vehicle (NEV) class, I am seeking practical methods to get these into the market. My priorities are to enable markets with semi-skilled labor and no viable manufacturing industry of note to be a location for a Wallaby EV plant. This is also a maneuver to minimize the incentive to just copy outright (but there's waaaay too much special sauce baked in to even come close to safety/performance/features) because there's a new game in town that pays well and helps people do real work.

My thought is that Russia is currently lacking domestic production and innovation on the global scale, and if offered an alternative to military industry, that it would be a viable and recognizable pivot for the benefit of Russia and its people.

For all I care they can burn all the CNG they want to make electricity and convert to EV. Then maybe the global petroleum market can begin to feel a change from a genuine leader - Russia. They hold a powerful position and I recognize that as any intelligent person should do right away.

I also acknowledge the difficulty of cultural mistrust - a lot of that I assert is generational. I believe Russians my age or younger (40 something) do care deeply about their national integrity and security. This is why I believe an incentive and acknowledgement of mutual benefit may be reasonable to offer and potentially get consideration.

Personally I'm tired of the suffering caused by arguments that escalate - many personal reasons. I've seen the effects of war first-hand from US Marines who served in Fallujah II. Also in Hurricane Katrina cleanup.

Thus, I respect Mr. Putin and also see that he is intelligent and cunning and knows a good thing when he sees it. Especially if it's obvious that the terms are beneficial to Russia as a whole and while it might not do much about the oligarchy structure at the top, my intent all along is to build better lives from the bottom up. That's why it's so simple and cheap to manufacture and I had to get my protections in line first.

Anything I can do to reduce the likelihood of a hot nuclear conflict in my lifetime or that of my family is a viable pursuit. Yes the odds are against me. However if I don't communicate the concept then it can't be shared with my intended audience.

Disclosure: I have already reached out to the Kingdom of Nepal with a similar offer because I befriended a half-dozen of them here in Texas and love their culture and work ethic and they fit in GREAT here. I kinda bet I'd do okay there. Would be the trip of a lifetime for this guy!
